                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>New York July 8<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1884<lb/></p>
                
            <p>Rev. Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>On my arrival here I found a letter of my<lb/> brother in San&#45;Francisco stating that having of late<lb/> sent &#36;100 to my son in Berlin&#44; and he himself<lb/> being in a critical condition he is for the<lb/> present unable to make &#91;&#94;&#93; me any <sic>farther</sic> remittance<lb/> in money and hopes I would find the means<lb/> for defraying my passage here among my<lb/> schoolmates. My brother however is greatly mistaken<lb/> I perceive that I could not do it without<lb/> running the risk of loosening the tie of friend&#45;<lb/>ship <del>that</del> holding me to them from boyhood.<lb/></p>
            <p>I therefore <sic>preffered</sic> applying to one or<lb/> the other gentleman disposing of some funds<lb/> of the Alliance Israelite or of the <sic>russian</sic> Emigrants<lb/> and in absence of Mr. Heilprin who might<lb/> have some faint recollection of my mission<lb/> of last year I applied to judge Isaacs of the<lb/> All&#58;Isr. who is  willing to grant me the passage<lb/> fees on condition that I bring him a letter<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>of recommendation from a trustworthy<lb/> gentleman who has any knowledge of my<lb/> mission which <del>was of</del> bore but a very private character.<lb/></p>
            <p>Having among other things mentioned <del>of</del> <lb/>your worthy name Mr&#58; Isaacs said a few<lb/> lines <del>o</del> from you in my behalf to that effect<lb/> would serve him as a most valuable pledge<lb/> for my deserving <del>htat</del> the grant I applied<lb/> for. I again venture to take recourse<lb/> to your noble and generous feelings<lb/> and leave it entirely to your good<lb/> <sic>judgement</sic> either to direct the letter<lb/> to Mr. Isaacs 115 Broadway  <del>or to s</del><lb/> and kindly informing &#94; me of it by a separate postal<lb/> card&#44; or sending  the letter to me to the<lb/> address on the foot of this&#91;.&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>Begging your pardon for intruding<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>so much on your valuable time and<lb/> for causing you so much trouble I trust<lb/> I shall be enabled to prove worthy<lb/> of the kind sympathy you bestowed<lb/> on me.</p>
            <p>I am Rev. Sir<lb/>
                your obedient servant<lb/>
                H. Krotowski<lb/>
                care of Mr&#58; A. Leszczynski<lb/>
                112 Rivington Str<lb/>
                New York				City<lb/></p>
        </body>
